{
  "_meta": {
    "schemaVersion": "1.0",
    "description": "Curated phrase \u2192 source-ID mapping for inline citation injection. When a doc's reference list contains source X, and the doc body mentions any of source X's phrases (case-sensitive, word-boundary anchored), the FIRST occurrence is wrapped with an inline citation marker pointing to that source's reference number. This is the Wikipedia / academic per-claim citation behaviour layered on top of the bibliography footer.",
    "rules": [
      "Phrases are matched case-sensitively to avoid false positives on common-noun substrings (e.g. 'data' or 'security').",
      "Word boundaries `(?<![\\w-])PHRASE(?![\\w-])` are required so 'GDPR' inside 'GDPR-compliant' still matches but 'aGDPRn' does not.",
      "Only the FIRST occurrence in each doc is annotated (Wikipedia convention).",
      "Matching is skipped inside code blocks, inline code, headings, existing markdown links, HTML tags, and the auto-generated footer block.",
      "If a source isn't already cited in the doc's reference list, no inline marker is added (we never invent citations out of band)."
    ],
    "schema": "source-id => [phrase, ...]"
  },

